Ford GoBike System Data Visulaization Project¶

By Onyeogulu Tochukwu Rowland¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The Ford Goike Data Set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the San Francisco Bay area. The data set. The data set will require some data wrangling techniques which includes merging of data stored in three(3) diferent csv file into one table before data visualization can commence.

In [15]:
# Convert start_time and end_time from 'object' type to 'datetime64[ns]'
df_merged['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_merged['start_time']).dt.date.astype('datetime64[ns]')
df_merged['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_merged['end_time']).dt.date.astype('datetime64[ns]')

# Convert user_type and rental_access_method from 'object' type to 'category'
df_merged['user_type'] = df_merged['user_type'].astype('category')
df_merged['rental_access_method'] = df_merged['rental_access_method'].astype('category')

  • Rental Access Method

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, we will be investigating distributions of individual variables. To find unusual points or outliers, and take a deeper look into each variable to clean things up and prepare to look at relationships between variables.

Univariate Exploration of the Main Features¶

In [22]:
# Univariate exploration of User type feature using bar chart
plt.figure(figsize = (16, 6))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
user_type_order = df_merged['user_type'].value_counts().index
sns.countplot(data = df_merged, x = 'user_type', color = base_color, order = user_type_order)
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.xticks(rotation = 0)

# get proportion taken by most common group for derivation
# of tick marks
n_points = df_merged.shape[0]
max_count = df_merged['user_type'].value_counts().max()
max_prop = max_count / n_points

# generate tick mark locations and names
tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.05)
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]

# create the plot 
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
sns.countplot(data =df_merged , x = 'user_type', color = base_color)
plt.yticks(tick_props * n_points, tick_names)
plt.ylabel('proportion')
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.xticks(rotation = 0);

Comment¶

The bar chart above show the ditribution of the user type feature in term of frequency and proportion. From the chart above, we can observe that we have we have more user type of category Subcriber than user type of category customer.

Univariate Exploration of the Support Features¶

# Univariate visualization of Duration in second 
plt.figure(figsize = [15, 5])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
bin_edges = np.arange(0, 2000, 50)
plt.hist(data = df_merged, x = 'duration_sec', bins =bin_edges, density = True)
plt.xticks([0, 200, 400, 600, 800, 1000, 1200, 1400, 1600, 1800, 2000])
plt.title('Fig 1: Distribution of Duration in Seconds')
plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds ');

# Univariate visualization of Log transformation of duration in seconds 
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
# Univariate visualization of Duration in second 
duration_log = np.log(df_merged['duration_sec'])
bin_edges = np.arange(3, duration_log.max()+0.05, 0.05)
plt.hist(duration_log, bins =bin_edges, density = True)
plt.title('Fig 2: Log tranformation distribution of Duration in Seconds')
plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds ');

Comment¶

The above, show the histogram ditribution of the duration in seconds variable in the data set. Outliers where detected in the data and Log transformation was used to transform the data to a range between 3 and 14. Fig 1 above shows that the distribution is right skewed. The log transformation histogram shows that the distrubution is normally distributed.

tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.05)
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]

# create the plot 
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
sns.countplot(data =df_merged , x = 'Start_month', color = base_color)
plt.yticks(tick_props * n_points, tick_names)
plt.ylabel('Proportion')
plt.xlabel('Start month')
plt.xticks(rotation = 0);

Comment¶

The chart above shows the ditribution of the prefered start month for riders. the chart above shows that the preferred start day is february followed closely by january and then march. The chart also shows that the least prefered month for riders is april.
